    <div class="lesson-content-title"><font color="red">Positron Release</font> or <font color="blue">Electron Capture</font>?</div>
    <div class="lesson-content-body">
        <strong>Proton-rich nuclei have two choices:  release a <font color="red">positive</font> charge, or
        capture a <font color="blue">negative</font> charge. </strong>
        
        <br/><br/>
        <strong><font color="red">Positron Emission (&#946;+)</font> </strong>:  
        Some nuclides are positron emitters, in which a proton changes into a 
        neutron with the emission of a positron and a neutrino. The energy of 
        these positrons is generally higher energy than found for beta-minus 
        decays. The <strong>positron</strong> itself is an anti-matter particle, so after losing kinetic energy will annihilate 
        with an electron.
        &#946;+ is used in PET imaging by detecting the two 
        511keV annihilation photons. 
